<HL>
   Man and Lemurs
   Strike a Good Deal
   On Island Off Africa
   ---
   An Ecological Plan May Save
   Both From Extinction;
   A Woman Brings Schools
   ----
   By Roger Thurow
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
01/10/91
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A1
</SO>
<CO>
   AFRIC
</CO>
<LP>
   RANOMAFANA, Madagascar -- It is a good morning in the rain
forest. The drizzle is light, the leeches are few and the
lemurs, bounding from tree to tree, are as happy as ever. So,
too, is their guardian, primatologist Patricia Wright, as she
returns to her cabin with two mouse lemurs, captured in small
metal boxes.
   The measuring begins. Left ear, three-quarters of an inch.
Tail, four inches. Right testicle, 0.4 inch. The littlest
lemur squirms in the palm of his inspector's hand. He is put
in a bag attached to a scale. Weight, 1 1/2 ounces.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   "They're the smallest primates in the world," says <PERSON>Ms.
Wright</PERSON>, her voice full of wonder.
   No sooner are the mouse lemurs sent scampering back to the
forest than a short, thin man with a big, wide smile enters
the cabin. He is <ORGANIZATION>Nala Edouard</ORGANIZATION>, the barefoot president of
Ambatolahy, a village of 31 peasant families on the edge of
the forest. His people, along with those in other villages,
have agreed to stop cutting down the trees, which amounts to
putting a hold on their agricultural expansion, in return for
development aid -- and a school. Now he has come to collect.
Again, <PERSON>Ms. Wright</PERSON> takes out her tape-measure, this time to
outline the foundation of the school she has promised them.
   "I walk into the forest and then into politics and then
back into the forest again," laughs the primatologist, a
professor at <ORGANIZATION>Duke University</ORGANIZATION>. "It's hard to even get my
clothes straight." The day before, she showed up at a meeting
with local officials in her knee-high mud boots. "I forgot,"
she says with slight embarrassment, "to change into my
shoes."
   So it goes in the quixotic quest to strike a balance
between conservation and development, in a country that
doesn't have enough money for either.
   <LOCATION>Madagascar</LOCATION>, an achingly beautiful island off the southeast
coast of <LOCATION>Africa</LOCATION>, is a land of sweeping distinctions: It is at
once one of the world's richest countries and one of its
poorest. It is also the most eroded spot on earth.
   The island's wealth is in its unique biological diversity.
Scientists estimate that 150,000 of the 200,000 identified
living things on <LOCATION>Madagascar</LOCATION>, which broke off from the African
mainland 160 million years ago, are found nowhere else. This
is true of its 13 species of lemurs -- ranging from the teddy
bear-faced indri, which begins and ends each day with a wail
that sounds like someone learning to play the clarinet, to
the tiny microcebus, a furry Kewpie doll with <PERSON>Bette Davis</PERSON>
eyes. The rosy periwinkle, a plant that produces the most
effective agent in combating childhood leukemia, is a native.
So are two-thirds of the world's chameleons and most of its
orchids.
   Yet <LOCATION>Madagascar</LOCATION> is pitifully poor, ranking among the
world's 10 most impoverished countries. Its 11 million
people, most of them farmers, have an average annual income
of <MONEY>$210</MONEY>. The government, in contrast, owes its international
creditors <MONEY>$283</MONEY> per person. Women live an average of 55 years,
men 52. Of every 1,000 babies born, 122 die before their
first birthday. Still, the population grows by <PERCENT>3%</PERCENT> a year. To
keep up, the Malagasy relentlessly push back the forest to
expand rice production.
   Through generations of such slash-and-burn agriculture,
the Malagasy have in effect been committing national suicide.
Eighty percent of the island's original forest is gone. From
the air, <LOCATION>Madagascar</LOCATION> looks as if is bleeding to death; its
rivers, red with eroded topsoil, spill into the Indian Ocean.
Already, 14 species of lemurs have become extinct, along with
the legendary "elephant bird" that reportedly stood 10 feet
tall, two giant turtles, an aardvark, a pygmy hippopotamus
and an unknown number of plants. Scientists say that if the
current pace of deforestation continues, in 20 to 40 years
the Malagasy themselves will be added to the list.
   "Yes, the lemurs are important. But the major species
under threat in <LOCATION>Madagascar</LOCATION> is the Malagasy," says <PERSON>Jose
Bronfman</PERSON>, the <ORGANIZATION>World Bank</ORGANIZATION> representative here. "Their major
source of life, the soil, is going into the sea."
   But from these barren hillsides and gaping gullies has
emerged an African rarity: Man and nature -- and their First
World surrogates, development experts and conservationists --
have become allies.
   "The environment will be saved if we reduce poverty," <PERSON>Mr.
Bronfman</PERSON>, a developmentalist, tells the conservationists.
"And poverty will be reduced if you save the environment."
   This elementary equation is the foundation of an ambitious
15-year environmental action plan drawn up by the Malagasy
government and a consortium of donor agencies from around the
world. Stamped on every page is an equally simple and
neglected principle: The Malagasy must be involved in their
own salvation.
   With the help of colleagues in the <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION>, <PERSON>Ms. Wright</PERSON>
persuaded the Malagasy government to set aside 103,000 acres
of rain forest as the <ORGANIZATION>Ranomafana National Park</ORGANIZATION>. But, with <PERCENT>90%</PERCENT>
of the local peasants' income coming from the forest -- from
freshwater crayfish and eels, wild fruit, honey, reeds for
weaving and from jobs as timber porters for the logging
companies -- laws wouldn't be enough to keep them out.
   "Our parents and grandparents taught us where to go in the
forest to make our living," says <PERSON>Jean Rafidison</PERSON>, a
29-year-old park guide who sells nuts and beans from the
forest on the side. "If you want us to stay out of the
forest, you must teach us, little by little, how to do things
differently."
   Little by little, Prof. <PERSON>Wright</PERSON> and her team of
researchers, backed with <MONEY>$3.4 million</MONEY> from the <ORGANIZATION>U.S. Agency
for International Development</ORGANIZATION>, are succeeding. Amid the
cluster of mud huts at the entrance to the park stands a
bamboo snack bar, where local peasants serve <ORGANIZATION>Coca-Cola</ORGANIZATION>. They
are learning that tourists, attracted by the forest and the
lemurs, bring money.
   While some researchers count lemurs and birds, others
count malnourished children. Some measure snails and geckos,
while others plan dams for irrigation and hydroelectricity. A
scientist from the <ORGANIZATION>Smithsonian Institution</ORGANIZATION> identifies 40,000
different insects in three weeks; a student from Duke hands
out conservation cartoons to the children.
   Up at the cabin, Prof. <PERSON>Wright</PERSON> slips into a pair of dress
loafers. It is time to visit the villagers at <LOCATION>Sahavondronona</LOCATION>.
   The elders are waiting on the hillside. They don't
understand the fuss over the lemurs -- "Don't you have them
in <LOCATION>America</LOCATION>?" asks one with a toothless grin -- but they trust
the woman who is bringing them a school.
   <PERSON>Pierre Rakotomanga</PERSON>, the village leader, says his people,
all 154 of them, are looking forward to a visit from the
American experts who can teach them to raise chickens and
pigs, and to extend the life of their rice paddies.
   His people have stopped pushing back the forest, he says,
but the need for food grows. <PERSON>Philomene Ravaoarisoa</PERSON>, mother of
11 children, steps forward to demonstrate. She rolls back the
frayed sleeves of her orange sweater and picks up the loose,
wrinkled skin of her boney right arm. "I'm getting thinner,"
she says. "My family is growing but the rice is the same."
   Still, when it came to picking a top development priority,
the villagers voted for a school. "We cannot eat a school,"
jokes <PERSON>Mr. Rakotomanga</PERSON>, "but it will educate our children.
They will learn how to live with the forest."
   Prof. <PERSON>Wright</PERSON> leaves with a broad smile. "We will furnish
the school, and put up posters of lemurs," she says
excitedly, bouncing down a gravel road on her way back to the
forest. "When you see lemurs when you are five, you remember
them all your life."
</TEXT>
