<HEAD>Wildlife Experts Draft Conservation Blueprint For the 1990s</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL RAEBURN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Editor</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ask <PERSON>Russ Mittermeier</PERSON> about his work, and he'll
talk about marketing, the hard sell, tough choices and money _ just
what you might expect from a sales executive or investment
counselor.
   <PERSON>Mittermeier</PERSON>, however, is a wildlife biologist and vice president
for science of the World Wildlife Fund. He's talking about
marketing conservation in countries where people struggle to find
their next meal. He's deciding how to get the most from a limited
pool of conservation dollars.
   His approach is a sign of a new discipline among
conservationists as they try to sharpen the conservation blueprint
for the <DATE>1990s</DATE>.
   ``I think we've got the potential to find the resources to make
conservation work,'' he said. ``We really have to make good
conservation an element of good development.''
   Other conservationists are thinking along similar lines. In
<DATE>January</DATE>, the <ORGANIZATION>World Resources Institute</ORGANIZATION> issued a report titled,
``The Crucial Decade: The <DATE>1990s</DATE> and The Global Environmental
Challenge.''
   ``If efforts to save species and biological diversity are to
succeed, a more coordinated, systematic and aggressive
international effort is needed,'' the report said. ``The <DATE>1990s</DATE> will
be the crucial decade for action on these pressing concerns.''
   Without a major effort, it said, ``irreparable damage will be
done to the world's environment, and the problems will prove
increasingly intractable, expensive and dominated by crises.''
   Mittermeier is trying to save endangered animals. Saving animals
means saving habitat. The most carefully protected animals cannot
survive if they have no place to live.
   So much has been said about the loss of habitat that the mere
recitation of statistics has lost its force. Each year, about
42,000 square miles of tropical forest are lost _ almost enough to
cover the state of <LOCATION>New York</LOCATION>.
   It's anybody's guess how many plant and animal species are
disappearing.
   In a report titled ``Biodiversity,'' Harvard biologist <PERSON>E.O.
Wilson</PERSON> tweaked the numbers and came up with this: Species are being
lost 1,000 to 10,000 times as fast as they were before human beings
arrived on the scene.
   ``By the <DATE>turn of the century</DATE>, much of the remaining tropical
forest is going to be in isolated parks surrounded by
development,'' said <PERSON>Mittermeier</PERSON>. ``There will be very few places
where natural evolutionary processes continue, where traditional
people continue to live traditional lifestyles.''
   <PERSON>Mittermeier</PERSON> and his colleagues have established three lines of
attack to try to limit the damage:
   _They've identified 10 ``threatened hot spots,'' small forested
regions in immediate danger. The hot spots cover two-tenths of <PERCENT>1
percent</PERCENT> of the <LOCATION>Earth</LOCATION>'s surface but harbor <PERCENT>27 percent</PERCENT> of all
tropical forest plant species.
   _They've targeted 13 countries as ``megadiversity countries,''
for their unusually rich animal and plant life. These countries
contain at least <PERCENT>60 percent</PERCENT> of the world's plant and animal species.
   _And they've identified what they call major wilderness areas,
the few places still mostly undisturbed where, if steps are taken
soon, evolution can continue and traditional people can survive.
   The ``threatened hot spots'' idea came from <PERSON>Norman Myers</PERSON>, a
senior fellow at the World Wildlife Fund.
   Without emergency aid, the 10 ``hot spots'' are likely to lose
<PERCENT>90 percent</PERCENT> of their forest cover within the next decade. That would
mean losing almost <PERCENT>7 percent</PERCENT> of the <LOCATION>Earth</LOCATION>'s 5 million to 30 million
plant and animal species.
   Apart from <LOCATION>Madagascar</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>New Caledonia</LOCATION>, the threatened hot
spots are in <LOCATION>South American</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>Asia</LOCATION>. <LOCATION>South America</LOCATION>'s are in the
<LOCATION>Choco</LOCATION> region of <LOCATION>Colombia</LOCATION>, western <LOCATION>Ecuador</LOCATION>, the uplands of western
<LOCATION>Amazonia</LOCATION> and the <LOCATION>Atlantic</LOCATION> coast of <LOCATION>Brazil</LOCATION>.
   <LOCATION>Asia</LOCATION>'s are in the <LOCATION>Philippines</LOCATION>, northern <LOCATION>Borneo</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Malaysia</LOCATION> and the
eastern <LOCATION>Himalayas</LOCATION>.
   Many of the species in these areas have already been lost or
will soon be lost, even if the areas are left untouched from now
on, <PERSON>Myers</PERSON> said. The rule of thumb is that for half of the species
to survive, the remaining forest must cover at least <PERCENT>10 percent</PERCENT> of
its original range.
   <PERSON>Myers</PERSON> says that is hardly ever the case.
   Mittermeier developed the concept of megadiversity countries.
``As a marketing device, it's tremendously valuable,'' he said. It
can be used in the megadiversity countries to excite the public
about conservation.
   ``It's a source of national pride,'' he said. ``It tells them,
in terms of natural resources, `we're pretty special.' It's an
effective way of selling conservation to them _ and to
foundations.''
   Because these countries contain at least <PERCENT>60 percent</PERCENT> and perhaps
even <PERCENT>80 percent</PERCENT> of the world's species, they ought to get <PERCENT>60
percent</PERCENT> or <PERCENT>70 percent</PERCENT> of conservation funds, <PERSON>Mittermeier</PERSON> has
proposed.
   The countries are <LOCATION>Mexico</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Venezuela</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Colombia</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Ecuador</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Peru</LOCATION>,
<LOCATION>Brazil</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Zaire</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Madagascar</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Indonesia</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Australia</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>India</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>China</LOCATION> and
<LOCATION>Malaysia</LOCATION>.
   <PERSON>Mittermeier</PERSON>, whose research specialty is primates, said <LOCATION>Brazil</LOCATION>,
<LOCATION>Zaire</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Indonesia</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>Madagascar</LOCATION> contain two-thirds of the world's
primate species. ``If we aren't successful in saving primate
species in these countries, we're going to lose a major portion of
the species,'' he said.
   ``We're not writing off the rest of the world. We're saying do
something in every country on <LOCATION>Earth</LOCATION>. But strategically, when we do
our planning, these countries should get a major chunk of the
interest, a major chunk of the investment.''
   There is some good news in this story: <PERSON>Mittermeier</PERSON> and company
have identified five major wilderness areas that have a good chance
of survival.
   ``These areas are not under immediate threat,'' he said. It
won't require a large investment to save them. ``You just have to
point out to the countries that this is something you should invest
in for the future,'' he said.
   They are in <LOCATION>New Guinea</LOCATION>, central <LOCATION>Zaire</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Venezuela</LOCATION> south of the
<LOCATION>Orinoco River</LOCATION>, parts of upper <LOCATION>Amazonia</LOCATION>, and in a region that cuts
across southern <LOCATION>Suriname</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Guyana</LOCATION> and <ORGANIZATION>French Guiana</ORGANIZATION>.
   The other bit of good news is that the <ORGANIZATION>World Bank</ORGANIZATION>, where
<PERSON>Mittermeier</PERSON> has served as manager of a task force on biodiversity,
takes conservation seriously.
   The bank's mission traditionally has been to foster development
in poor countries, which often put it in conflict with
environmentalists. It made an important change in <DATE>1986</DATE> with the
adoption of a wildlands policy.
   ``Wildlands can often contribute significantly to economic
development,'' the bank said. ``The <ORGANIZATION>Bank</ORGANIZATION>'s policy is therefore to
seek a balance between preserving the environmental values of the
world's more important remaining wildlands and converting some of
them to more intensive, shorter term use.''
   <PERSON>Mittermeier</PERSON> said conservationists should do two things to try to
save remaining forests. The first is to expand the number and size
of protected areas. But that has its limitations.
   ``They are expensive and will compose, at best, only five to <PERCENT>10
percent</PERCENT> of the world's land area,'' <PERSON>Mittermeier</PERSON> said.
   The second tactic is to encourage profitable use of the forests
that doesn't destroy them. Researchers recently found, for example,
that harvesting latex, fruit and wood from a managed forest was
three times as profitable as cutting it down to produce pulpwood or
raise crops or cattle, <PERSON>Mittermeier</PERSON> said.
   ``Development inevitably comes back to depending on natural
resources,'' he said, ``and if you don't use natural resources
wisely, your development efforts and your global economy are
eventually going to go down the tube.''
