<DESCRIPT>  CONSERVATION  </DESCRIPT>
<LEADPARA>  SOME people consider the destruction of the world's rain forests the most
frightening of all recent ecological developments. The tropical rain forests,
located in a narrow region near the equator in Africa, South and Central
America, and Asia, are disappearing so fast that by the year 2000, 80 percent
of them may be gone.;    What does this mean? Consider:  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Living  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  HOW TO KEEP THE RAIN FORESTS ALIVE  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  EarthWorks
Write to John Javna in care of EarthWorks, P.O. Box 419149, Kansas City, Mo.
64141.  </MEMO>
<TEXT>     (check)  Although rain forests make up only <PERCENT>2 percent</PERCENT> of the world's
surface, more than half the world's wild plant, animal and insect species live
there. Less than <PERCENT>1 percent</PERCENT> of these have ever been studied, yet many are
already being wiped out.;    (check)  More than <PERCENT>25 percent</PERCENT> of prescription
drugs are derived from rain forest materials. Rain forest plants and animals
are the sources of drugs that lower blood pressure, treat Parkinson's disease,
treat glaucoma, inhibit cancer cell growth, etc.;    (check)  An estimated
1,000 native tribes are being threatened with extinction as the rain forests
are depleted.;    Why are the rain forests being cut down? To make money. The
forests are often harvested for logging or leveled for cattle ranching.;   
What can we do? Many experts believe that the only way to save the rain
forests is to develop an alternative, "sustainable" rain forest economy --
that is, create an economy based on using nuts, leaves and other materials
that can be harvested from the rain forests without threatening their
survival. Scientists estimate that the sustainable bounty of the forest is
worth twice as much in the long run as the timber that can be logged or the
cattle that can be raised there.;    Frankly, it's up to us to provide the
market for sustainable rain forest products. And I'm pleased to report that a
growing number of them are available. One non-profit group, called Cultural
Survival, distributes items like cashews, <LOCATION>Brazil</LOCATION> nuts, soaps, bath oil, dried
fruit and handicrafts nationwide. Contact the company at <ORGANIZATION>53A Church St.</ORGANIZATION>,
<LOCATION>Cambridge</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Mass.</LOCATION> 02138, or at 617-495-2562, for a list of its products. It can
also supply educational materials.;    More sustainable products are popping
up all the time, so shop around; check out store and catalogs. Look for
products that come from the fruits of the rain forest but don't depend on
cutting down trees. As you find them, spread the word. For more information,
contact: The rain forest Action Network, 301 Broadway, Suite A, <LOCATION>San Francisco</LOCATION>,
<LOCATION>Calif.</LOCATION> 94133. Send a self-addressed, stamped envelope for an updated list of
sustainable rain forest products.;    One individual can make a difference.
When many of his friends admired -- and even coveted -- his Latin American
straw hat, a "sustainable" product made from the leaves of rain forest plants,
<PERSON>Stefan Schinzinger</PERSON> began importing them. The fedora-style straw hat, braided
by Guatemalan Indians, is now available through Gardener's Supply
(800-548-4784). Another of his models, the <LOCATION>Palmata</LOCATION>, is available through the
<ORGANIZATION>Nature Co.</ORGANIZATION> (800-227-1114). Schinzinger also imports buttons made from the nuts
of the <ORGANIZATION>Tagua</ORGANIZATION> palm -- 10 million buttons in <DATE>1990</DATE> alone. Useful as a substitute
for ivory or plastic, they support a cottage industry in <LOCATION>Ecuador</LOCATION>. They're used
by <ORGANIZATION>The North Face</ORGANIZATION>, Seventh Generation and others.  </TEXT>
