<HEAD>`Outlook Is Grim' For Tropical Jungles, Scientist Says</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Tuesday AMs report.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ED SCHAFER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ST. LOUIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The destruction of millions of acres of
tropical jungles each year by peasant farmers and others is a
problem for the developed nations as well as the Third World and
requires economic and educational solutions, say scientists at a
leading plant research institution.
   The <ORGANIZATION>Missouri Botanical Garden</ORGANIZATION>, known for its man-made tropical
atmosphere in the so-called ``Climatron'' designed by <PERSON>Buckminster
Fuller</PERSON>, is working to halt the decimation of the world's real
tropical jungles.
   ``The outlook is pretty grim,'' said biologist <PERSON>Peter H. Raven</PERSON>,
director of the garden. ``Although tropical forests once covered at
least <PERCENT>12 percent</PERCENT> of the globe _ an area about twice the size of
<LOCATION>Europe</LOCATION> _ they have already been reduced to about half that.''
   ``Currently, the forests are being cleared or degraded at the
rate of about 60 million acres a year. That's an area about half
the size of <LOCATION>California</LOCATION>.''
   Raven said roughly half of all known plant and animal species on
<LOCATION>Earth</LOCATION> are found in the tropical forests. At the current rate of
destruction, as many as 60,000 species of plants will be extinct by
the year <DATE>2020</DATE>.
   ``The plant-rich tropics supply man with a wealth of food crops,
medicines and other useful products,'' said <PERSON>Dr. Enrique Forero</PERSON>,
director of research at the garden. ``But they are being destroyed
rapidly.''
   The chief culprits, <PERSON>Forero</PERSON> said, are loggers and slash-and-burn
peasant farmers. The loggers obviously need the trees to stay in
business and the farmers often have to destroy the forests to feed
themselves and their families.
   And the scientists say the situation can only get worse unless
something is done to stop it.
   ``At present, over half the people in the world live in
countries that are at least partly tropical, excluding <LOCATION>China</LOCATION>,''
<PERSON>Forero</PERSON> said. ``Nearly a third of these people are already living in
extreme poverty and with current rates of growth, the human
population of these countries will double in less than 30 years.''
   ``How can you tell these starving people that you are going to
save the very things they have to destroy in order to sustain their
already meager existence,'' asked <ORGANIZATION>Raven</ORGANIZATION>. ``Education and political
and economic stability are obviously the keys. That and
understanding.''
   Which is why, <ORGANIZATION>Raven</ORGANIZATION> said, the garden has committed itself to an
all-out effort to explore, document and save the forests.
   With a staff of 70 researchers and technicians, including many
who live permanently in the tropics, the garden makes up one of the
world's largest active field research programs in tropical botany.
   The goals, the scientists said, are to collect the plant species
before they become extinct and to teach the impoverished farmers
how to live in the forest without destroying it.
   With the growing knowledge of genetics, they said, it is
important that the genes, the biological blueprints, of the
endangered species be saved.
   ``To lose this genetic capital through massive extinctions just
as we are developing our capabilities to explore its potential
would indeed be a tragedy,'' <ORGANIZATION>Raven</ORGANIZATION> said. ``The developments in
genetics make the specter of extinction even worse,'' <ORGANIZATION>Raven</ORGANIZATION> said.
``For each species of plant or animal lost to extinction, you're
losing the potential for another 20,000 to 30,000 variants in the
future.''
   Many of the plants, scientists say, could almost certainly be
developed into cheaper, easy-to-grow sources of highly nutritious
food. Others could be converted into abundant sources of new
medicines.
   Another important part of the garden's program is to lend
technical assistance to and train scientists from developing
tropical countries through cooperative agreements.
   ``Unfortunately, only <PERCENT>6 percent</PERCENT> of the scientists working on the
problem live in the countries involved,'' <ORGANIZATION>Raven</ORGANIZATION> said. ``We must
change that. Momentum to implement the innovative conservation and
development strategies needed to deal with these urgent problems
ultimately must come from the affected countries themselves,''
<ORGANIZATION>Raven</ORGANIZATION> said.
   The backbone of the garden's research, the scientists said, is
its herbarium, or plant collection. Along with the <ORGANIZATION>New York
Botanical Garden</ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION>Smithsonian</ORGANIZATION> Institution, the <LOCATION>Missouri</LOCATION>
herbarium is one of the three largest in the <LOCATION>United States</LOCATION> and
among the 12 largest in the world.
   Started by garden founder <PERSON>Henry Shaw</PERSON> in the <DATE>1850s</DATE>, the <LOCATION>Missouri</LOCATION>
herbarium now contains samples of more than 3.5 million species and
is expected to expand to 4.5 million within the next decade.
   Pointing to a large map showing the locations of the garden's
researchers in Central and <LOCATION>South America</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>Africa</LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION>Raven</ORGANIZATION> said of
the encroachment on the forests: ``It won't be stopped soon.
   ``But there are encouraging signs. What people have to learn is
that conservation and development are really two sides of the same
coin.''
   ``Producers and consumers have to learn that they have a common
problem. It can all be done, but it won't be easy.''
</TEXT>
